### Common Pitfalls

| Wrong | Right |
|-------|-------|
| `fn foo()` | `fun foo()` |
| `foo() -> int` | `foo() : int` |
| `return x` | just `x` (last expression) |
| `"a" ++ "b"` | `"a" + "b"` |
| `str(n)` | `show(n)` |
| `else { () }` | `else { }` |
| `my-variable` | `my_variable` |
| `assert(x \|> f == val)` | `let r = x \|> f; assert(r == val)` |
| `assert(match ...)` | `let r = match ...; assert(r == ...)` |
| `items[i]` (list index) | recursive pattern match |
| `let rec aux(x) = ...` | top-level `fun aux(x) => ...` (no `let rec` in hica) |
| inner `fun` closing over outer param for recursion | pass state as an explicit accumulator argument to a top-level helper |
| `parse_int(s) \|> unwrap()` | `parse_int` returns `maybe<int>` — use `unwrap_maybe_or(0)` or match `Some`/`None` |
| `{ ...p, score: p.score + 1 }` (struct spread) | NOT supported — reconstruct fully: `Player { score: p.score + 1, name: p.name }` |
| `show(x)` inside `"...{show(x)}..."` with generic `x` | Koka can't resolve `show` overload for unconstrained type — use `"{x}"` directly (interpolation calls show implicitly), or annotate the parameter type |
| Claiming list match functions are polymorphic when they use `show` | `show(x)` requires a concrete type — add a type annotation e.g. `xs: list<int>` when using `show` on elements |
| `fun swap((a, b)) => (b, a)` (tuple param destructuring) | NOT supported — parse error. Destructure inside the body: `fun swap(pair) { match pair { (a, b) => (b, a) } }` |
| `is_empty(xs)` on a list | `is_empty` takes a `string`, not a list — use `match xs { [] => ..., _ => ... }` to check for an empty list |
| `head(xs)` as an `int` seed value | `head` returns `maybe<T>` not `T` — use `match xs { [] => 0, [x, ..rest] => ... }` or `head_or(xs, 0)` from `std/list` |
| Calling `id(42)` then `id("hello")` in the same function | Type inference monomorphizes within a single `fun` or `main` body: `id` locks to `int` at first call. However, each `test` block has its own independent scope, so calling `id(42)` and `id("hello")` in the *same test block* is valid. Never mix types within one `fun main()`. |
